THat In Confessione Fidei Ecclesiarum Belgicarum oblata Synodo Dordrechtanae, inter acta hujus Synodi pag. 308 primae partis Edit. Elsevir. anni 2600. approbata est haec Confessio in Synodo protestantium Galliae Vitriaci habita 25. Maii anno 1583. Necessarium est, aut omnia, quae ad salutem nostram requiruntur in Iesu Christo non esse, aut si in eo sunt omnia, tum eum qui fide Iesum Christum possidet, totum salutem habere: asserere itaque Iesum Christum minimè sufficere; sed aliis quoque praeter ipsum • pus esse, horrenda omninò in Deum blasphemia est. Nam inde sequeretur, ipsum Christum ex parte tantùm servatorem esse. Meritò igitur dicimus cum Paulo nos sola Fide justificari. 'tis Blasphemie against God, to say, that wee are not Justified by faith alone; & that 'tis not enough, to be, & have faith in JESUS-CHRIST; that to expound Thesaurus disput. Sedan. th. 22. de Justificatione patte 1. tom. 1. pag. 625. Hominibus quibus propositum est Christianam Fidem cuniculis subruere & machinis evertere, Sathan suggessit compendiosam viam, quâ unius vicis (Fidei) corruptione, totam Fidem Christianam pessumdarent; & Fidem Christianorum à Christi gratiâ, ad suas ipsoru • virtutes & opera converterent. as wee do the word faith, in this point of justification, is to overthrow the faith & Christian Religion;
that in Philippus Melancton in Epitome renovarae Doctrinae Ecclesiasticae, tom. 2. operum pag. 4. Nec in Poenitentia, nec in justificatione requirunt Spiritum Sanctum; sed rationis conatu contenti sunt, qui tamen nihil aliud, nisi mera Hypocrisis est. Justification and Repentance, wee cōtent our selves with humane force, rejecting the assistance of the holy Ghost; that Guilielmus Bucamus loco 31. de Justificat. paragr. 48. pag. 356. Christi meritis diffisi, confugiunt ad merita bonorum operum & fuffragia Sanctorum. through distrust of the Merrits of Jesus-Christ, wee have recours to the Meritts of our worcks, & to the suffrages of the Saints; that Andraeas Rivetus in Catholico orthodoxe, seu summâ Controvers. quaest. 1. Prooemiali de Haeresibus tom. 1. pag. 39. Pelagiani docebant hominem justum in hac vitâ nullum omninò hebere peccatum, &c. Tales & similes Haereses in Papatu vigent: omnes docent posse hominem in hac vita perfecte legem implere, unde sequitur eum esse sine peccato. Franciscus Burmanus in Synopsi Theologica l. 6. c. 7. paragr. 20. tom. 2. pag. 232. Adoptarum Pontificii Pelagianorum impeccantiam, dùm regenitos omni peccato mortali, omnique malo habitu carere posse contendunt, ac in Synodo Tridentina Iustos in omni opere venialiter, nedum mortaliter peccare negant, quam sententiam sine manifesta hypocrisi, & divinae L • gis violatione tueri non possunt. wee adopt the Error of the Pelagians concerning the Impeccability of the Iust, or that the Iust sin not; that Ioannes Calvinus l. 4. Institut. c. 15. §. 10. pag. 351. Pe • spicuum est quàm falsum sit, quod docuerunt pridem nonnulli, in quo alii persistunt, per Baptismum solvi nos & eximi ab originali peccato, & à corruptione, quae ab Adam in universam posteritatem propagata est, atque in eamdem justitiam naturaeque puritatem restitui, • quam abtinuisset Adam, si in ea, in quá primùm creatus fuerat, naturae integritata stetisset. wee
wee teach, that Baptisme gives us the same degree of sanctity, that Adam had, if he had Remain'd in the state of Inocence; that Theodorus Beza in Antithesi Papatus & Christianismi tract. Theologic. c. 7. tom. 1. pag. 63. Romani originis peccatum levi aquae aspergine, volunt statim ac penitùs in nobis elui, & ejus reliquias docent peccati rationem non habere, nisi consensus accedat, quam Doctrinam prorsùs diabolicam esse affirmamus. Hieronymus Zanchius operum Theologicorum Vol. 1. tom. 4. Edit Gamoneti anni 1605. pag. 71. l. 1. de peccato Originali cap. 5. thesi 3. de Concupiscentia in renatis. Non potest negligi haec Controversia, quin negligatur gloria Christi, &c. Ergo si nobis cordi est gloria Christi & salus nostra non debemus permittere, ut Pontificia sententia obtineat in Ecclesia; sed pro viribus expugnanda est. Ioannes Heydeggerus in Anatome Conc. Trid. ad sess. 5. de Peccato Originali. tom. 1. pag. 131. Totum dogma de expunctione Peccati Originalis per Baptismum, ad avaritiae & suberbiae incudem formatum est. Id enim dant operam Clerici, ut Sacramentorum, qua ab ipsis conferuntur, excollatur efficacia, & indè ministerio suo lucrum ac honos accrescat. our doctrine, according which original sin, is taken away by Baptisme, is diabolicall; that it would be to the honnour & glory of IESUS-CHRIST, & of salvation not to suffer it, & that it was forged upon the anvile of Coveteousness, & of the ambition of the Eclesiasticks, for to raise the Efficacie of the Sacraments they administer, & for to augment the honnour & Revenues of their Ministry;
that Charles Drelincourt Minister of Charenton in his Abridgement of Controversies c. 72. pag. 300. of the Edition, of the year 1674. The Roman Church teacheth that Concupiscence Remains after Baptisme: by which the Roman Church Confesseth that the sin Remains after Baptisme, Thesaurus Disput. Sedan. th. 53. de Baptismo parte 3. tom. 1. pag 787. Apostolum Tridentini Patres ausi sunt accusare oscitantiae & locutionis impropriae & non verae dicentes Apostolum concupiscentiam appellasse peccatum, non quod verè & propriè peccatum esset in renatis, &c. Joannes Heydeggerus loco mox laudato. tom. 1. pag. 131. Viderit Synodus Tridentina, an non Scripturam sacram Anathemate, nefariè ac veluti 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 perculserit. wee fall into Contradiction, saying that the Concupiscence is not (to speake properly) à sinn in the Regenerated; and that it is to accuse the Apostle not to have thought of what he writt, to pronounce Anathema to the holy scripture, & comitt à kind of a deicide: that Philippus Meloncton in Epitome renovatae Doctrinae Ecclesiasticae tom. 2. pag. 4. Aristotelici Theologi docent mereri nos nostris viribus & nostro conatu gratiam. The Minister Noguier, in his answer to the Exposition of the doctrine of the Church by my Lord, the Bishop of Meaux, then Bishop of Comdom 1. part. c. 12. pag. 103. My lord of comdom, doth he not give to understand, that he approves of all that the schoole of Rome holds & Maintains, that if man by his free will, cannot do works which Merrit Eternall life, he may have movements which disposes him to receave grace, which in their Langua • ge is caled Merit of congruity. The seacond answer to the same worke of the Bishop of Comdom, by à Nameless author pag. 85. The Councill of Trent teacheth that of our selves, wee prepare our selves, and wee dispose our selves to grace, by which wee are Regenerated. Franciscus Burmannus in Synopsi Theolog. l. 6. 8. §. 25. tom. 2. pag. 241. In eo errant Pontificii, quod meritum operibus ante gratiam factis tribuunt. Jurieu in his book intituled à preservatif. p. 150. art. 7. The Councill of Trent by her Ambiguitys & Rambling expressions, has left semipelagianisme, & even Pelagianisme in their intire profession. according to our Doctrine,
of our selves, wee prepare our selves for graee, & that wee merrit it by our works which precede it, as the Pelagians believed; & that the councill of Trent has confirm'd semipelagianisme, & even Pelagianisme, in every point; that Philippus Melancton, in Commentar, ad cap. 3. Epist ad Romanos tom 3. operum pag. 953. Tantùm tribuunt Christo, quod principium & occasionem merendi nobis promeruerit, ipsi sic loquuntur Christum meruisse primam gratiam, posteà sepeliunt eum & fingunt otiosum esse, & imaginantur homines meriti remissionem peccatorum & justo esse propter propriam impletionem Legis. JESUS-CHRIST, is to yow but an occasiō to merrit; & that after he has merited for us the first grace, wee believe, that he is of no more use to us, and that wee alone merrit the Remission of our sins; that Thesaurus Disputat. Sedanens. th. 5. de Fide justificante & operibus parte 3. tom. 1. pag. 637. An quidquam est Evangelio magis adversum, aut Religionis Christianae magis Fundamenta convellens, quàm haec Doctrina, quae docet hominem praeditum Fide justificante posse damnari. wee teach, that à man may be damn'd, haveing à Iustifieing faith; that Guillielmus Bucamus loco 31. de Justificatione §. 48. pag. 356. Error Pontificiorum 9. Mariae Virgini autoritatem justificandi tribuunt; Papae potestatem vendendi remissionem peccatorum. wee
give or atribute to the virgin, the power to Iustifie us, & to the Pope the power to sell the Remission of sins; thatIoannes Heydeggerus in Anatome Concilii Tridentini, tom. 1. pag. 261. Quid statuendum de hac fastuosa Doctrina, nostram Doctrinam de meritis operum intelligit. The author of the Considerations upon the Circular letters, & Pastorall advertisement of the Clergie of France to those of the Pretended Reformed Religion, consideration the fourth pag. 111. The thought of Meritt is of it selfe à thought of Pride. Essentially Contrary to true Godlynesse. Iurieu in the preservatiff pag. 149. Wherfore have wee so much Iealousies against this word Merritt, which is superbe & opposiit to Christian Humility. Ioannes Heydeggerus ad sess. 6. Conc. Trident. tom. 1. pag. 131. Ipsos Pharisaeos Romanenses, suffarcinatos persuasione propriae justitiae. our opinion of Merrit is full of Contempt & pride, Essentially contrary to true piety; & that wee are Pharises stuffed with the persuasion of our one Righteousness, for that wee ought to believe according to the divinity of the Pretended Reformed, that all the best works of the Iust, meritt but Eternall damination. Udalricus Zuinglius in explanatione Articulorum seu Propositionum suarum art. 20. tom. 1. operum fol. 46. Neque ullum opus existimandum est ut meritum, sed hoc cogitandum potius, omnia nostra opera nihil mereri, quàm damnationem.
